## Description

`Interop/TypeMap/TypeMapApp/TypeMapApp.cmd` fails deterministically in all R2R configurations because of a disconnect between CrossGen2 and the runtime when a `TypeMapAssemblyTarget` references an unresolvable assembly (e.g., `"DoesNotExist"`).

When CrossGen2 fails to resolve an assembly target, it catches the exception and sets error stubs on the external/proxy type maps (state=0), but `AddTargetModule` is never called, leaving `TargetModules` empty. CrossGen2 then emits a `TypeMapAssemblyTargets` entry with count=0 while marking the external/proxy maps as invalid. At runtime, `HasTypeMapAssemblyTargets` finds this empty entry → returns `true` with count=0 → sets `hasPrecachedTargets = true` → skips fallback to attribute processing → `FileNotFoundException` is never thrown.

**Primary fix (runtime — `assemblynative.cpp`):** The outer `if` block already enters when any of the three precached maps (targets, external, proxy) are missing. The assembly target attribute re-processing is now unconditional within that block, since the outer condition already guarantees at least one map needs fallback. The `AssemblyTargetProcessor` already deduplicates via `_toProcess`/`_processed` SHash collections, so re-processing is always safe.

```cpp
if ((newExternalTypeEntry != nullptr && !hasPrecachedExternal) ||
    (newProxyTypeEntry != nullptr && !hasPrecachedProxy) ||
    !hasPrecachedTargets)
{
    // Fall back to attribute parsing for the assembly targets...
    // The AssemblyTargetProcessor already deduplicates, so re-processing is safe.
    ProcessTypeMapAttribute(
        TypeMapAssemblyTargetAttributeName,
        assemblies,
        groupTypeMT,
        currAssembly);
    // ...
}
```

**Complementary cleanup (CrossGen2 — `TypeMapAssemblyTargetsNode.cs` and `TypeMapMetadata.cs`):** Skip emitting `TypeMapAssemblyTargets` entries only for groups where assembly target attributes were present but all failed to resolve. A `HasAssemblyTargetAttributes` flag on the `Map` class distinguishes "no `TypeMapAssemblyTarget` attributes exist" (should still emit a count=0 precached entry) from "attributes exist but all targets failed to resolve" (should skip so the runtime falls back to attribute processing). This avoids regressing groups without any assembly target attributes, which would otherwise be forced down the unnecessary fallback path.

```csharp
// TypeMapMetadata.cs — Map class
public bool HasAssemblyTargetAttributes { get; set; }

// TypeMapAssemblyTargetsNode.cs — narrowed skip condition
foreach (var map in _assemblyTypeMaps.Maps)
{
    if (map.Value.TargetModules.Count == 0 && map.Value.HasAssemblyTargetAttributes)
        continue; // only skip when target attributes were present but all failed
    // ...emit entry...
}
```

**Test added (`TypeMapApp.cs`):** Added `Validate_MissingAssemblyTarget_DoesNotAffectGroupsWithoutTargets` to verify that groups without `TypeMapAssemblyTarget` attributes (like `TypicalUseCase`) continue to work correctly alongside groups with failing targets (like `UnknownAssemblyReference`). When running in R2R mode, the test also validates the `.r2rdump` file to confirm that `ExternalTypeMaps`, `ProxyTypeMaps`, and `TypeMapAssemblyTargets` sections are all present in the R2R image, ensuring CrossGen2 correctly emitted entries for groups without assembly target attributes.

